{{Orphan|date=November 2015}}
The '''Anti-Fascist Committee of German Workers in Romania''' ({{lang-de|Antifaschistischen Komitees der deutschen Werktätigen in Rumänien}}), originally the '''German Anti-Fascist Committee''' ({{lang-de|Deutsche Antifaschistische Komitee}}; {{lang-ro|Comitetul Antifascist German}}), was an organization for [[Germans of Romania|ethnic Germans in Romania]]. Emmerich Stoffel was the chairman of the Committee and Philipp Geltz its secretary.<ref name="a">{{cite book|title=Dokumentation der Vertreibung der Deutschen aus Ost-Mitteleuropa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GYhQAQAAIAAJ|volume=3|date=1953|publisher=Bundesministerium für Vertriebene|page=101}}</ref> The Committee was based in [[Bucharest]] and published the newspaper ''[[Neuer Weg (Bucharest)|Neuer Weg]]'' ('New Path').<ref name="a"/>
By the late 1940s the post-[[Second World War]] wave of discriminations against the German minority in Romania had subdued.<ref name="Illyés1982">{{cite book|author=Elemér Illyés|title=National minorities in Romania: change in Transylvania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPS2AAAAIAAJ|year=1982|publisher=East European monographs|page=300}}</ref> At its meeting in December 1948, the [[Politburo|Political Bureau]] of the [[Central Committee]] of the [[Romanian Workers Party]] adopted a 'Resolution of the National Question' which outlined the need for the formation of a German Anti-Fascist Committee and a German-language newspaper.<ref name="BarcanMillitz1978">{{cite book|author1=Monica Barcan|author2=Adalbert Millitz|title=The German Nationality in Romania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0mlpAAAAMAAJ|year=1978|publisher=Meridiane|pages=36}}</ref> The Anti-Fascist Committee of German Workers in Romania was founded in March 1949 by a number of ethnic German party members, along with its organ ''Neuer Weg''.<ref name="MüllerLandeskunde2002">{{cite book|author1=Annett Müller|author2=Arbeitskreis für Siebenbürgische Landeskunde|title=Abschied in Raten: vom Neuen Weg zur Allgemeinen Deutschen Zeitung für Rumänien : der Wandel der Zeitung nach der massenhaften Auswanderung der Deutschen aus Romänien|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ijcbAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Hora|isbn=978-3-929848-23-6|page=74}}</ref><ref name="Merten2013">{{cite book|author=Ulrich Merten|title=Forgotten Voices: The Expulsion of the Germans from Eastern Europe after World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EXxUAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA279|date=15 August 2013|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-5258-6|page=279}}</ref> The Committee was tasked with mobilizing support for the communist government amongst ethnic German labourers.<ref name="Merten2013"/> The Committee was one of a number of ethnic mass organizations in Romania at the time, alongside the [[Jewish Democratic Committee]], Union of Slav Democratic Cultural Associations, the Hungarian Popular Union, the Democratic Committee of the Russian and Ukrainian Peoples, the Democratic Greek Committee and the Democratic Armenian Committee.<ref name="Străine1952">{{cite book|author=Romania. Ministerul Afacerilor Străine|title=Enemies of Peace and Freedom of the Peoples|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVfVAAAAMAAJ|year=1952|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs|page=89}}</ref>
