{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}} {{Use British English|date=March 2015}} '''Whiteway Colony''' was a [[residential community]] in the [[Cotswolds]] in the parish of [[Miserden]] near [[Stroud, Gloucestershire|Stroud]], [[Gloucestershire]], United Kingdom. The community was founded in 1898 by [[Tolstoyan]]s and today has no spare land available with over sixty homes and 120 colonists.<ref name="DandD">{{cite web|url=http://www.diggersanddreamers.org.uk/index.php?fld=super_region&val=South%20West%20England&one=dat&two=det&sel=whiteway |title=Whiteway Colony |publisher=[[Diggers and Dreamers]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306202249/http://www.diggersanddreamers.org.uk/index.php?fld=super_region&val=South%20West%20England&one=dat&two=det&sel=whiteway|archive-date=2012-03-06}}</ref> At the beginning, [[private property]] was rejected and [[personal property]] shared; however, today the colonists' homes are privately owned and sold at market value.<ref name="Alston2010">{{Cite web | title = Tolstoy's Guiding Light | last = Alston | first = Charlotte | work = [[History Today]] | date = 10 October 2010 | accessdate = 2018-07-19 | url = https://www.historytoday.com/charlotte-alston/tolstoys-guiding-light | quote = }}</ref><ref name="Edghill2003">{{Cite web | title = What a carry-on in the Cotswolds | last = Edghill | first = Sarah | work = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date = 1 February 2003 | accessdate = 2018-07-19 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3310858/What-a-carry-on-in-the-Cotswolds.html | quote = }}</ref> As the colony abandoned Tolstoy's philosophy it has been regarded by many, including [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi|Mohandas Gandhi]] who visited in 1909, as a failed Tolstoyan experiment.<ref name="Hunt2005">{{cite book|last=Hunt|first=James D. |title=An American Looks at Gandhi: Essays in Satyagraha, Civil Rights, and Peace|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kNvTdX52nw8C&pg=PA43|year=2005|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-35-4|pages=43–}}</ref>
==History== The colony was set up in 1898 by a [[Quaker]] journalist, Samuel Veale Bracher, along with other Tolstoyans. Bracher purchased {{convert|41|acre}} along with seeds, tools, materials and provisions. The colonists then burnt the property deeds on the end of a pitchfork in a symbolic rejection of the notion of [[property]]. [[Aylmer and Louise Maude|Aylmer Maude]] led the founding board of trustees for the colony.
The early settlers had [[Utopian socialism|utopian socialist]] ideals, sharing provisions and going [[Back-to-the-land movement|back-to-the-land]]. The founding colonists numbered about eight but over time the community rose to forty with anyone welcome. However Bracher, his family and other founders left the colony soon afterwards as they became increasingly frustrated with the other residents' idleness.<ref name="Alston2010" /><ref name="Hart1906">{{cite book|last=Hart|first=W. C. |title=Confessions of an anarchist| url=https://archive.org/stream/confessionsofana00hartrich#page/78/mode/2up|year=1906|publisher=E. Grant Richards|pages=79–81}}</ref>
Early life in the colony was spartan with some residents using a barn as shelter - piped water did not arrive until 1949 and [[electricity]] not until 1954. The site was originally open land surrounding Whiteway House but is now heavily wooded and home to a collection of mainly wooden buildings - as no one owns the land, mortgages could not be obtained so people had to build their own houses. A court ruling in 1955 established that nobody owns the legal title for the land.<ref name="ConatyLarge">{{Cite web | title = Commons Sense-Co-operative place making and the capturing of land value for 21st century Garden Cities | editor1-first=Pat|editor1-last=Conaty|editor2-first=Martin|editor2-last=Large|publisher=Co-operatives UK | date = n.d. |via=[[Internet Archive]] | url = https://archive.org/stream/Commons_Sense-Co-operative_place_making_and_the_capturing_of_land_value_for_21st/Commons_Sense-Co-operative_place_making_and_the_capturing_of_land_value_for_21st_century_Garden_Cities_djvu.txt }}</ref> A communal hall was built by residents in 1924 to house social activities and a school, and a swimming pool was built in 1969. Whiteway Colony is still in existence today and houses, among others, descendants of its original settlers. Though it no longer has an explicitly [[anarchist]] character, today's residents are aware, and proud, of its origins. Traces of them run through the community still, the best examples being the continued use and maintenance of communal facilities (hall, swimming pool and playing field). In addition, the governance of the community is still done by a [[general meeting]] of its residents.
Over the years residents have included immigrant [[anarchist]]s, [[conscientious objector]]s and refugees from the [[Spanish Civil War]], as well as co-operative ventures such as Protheroe's Bakery (known in the local area for the quality of its bread), the Cotswold Co-operative Handicraft guild and the Co-operative Gardening Group. For a period the anarchist newspaper ''[[Freedom newspaper|Freedom]]'' was produced here by [[Thomas Keell]].
